Issues.Body:
Previously, `.get()` always included `null` in its type, regardless of whether we can prove the control exists (i.e. is non-null). By pushing the `AbstractControl` container type into the helpers, we can explicitly include `null` in the failure cases (but *not* in the success cases), allowing us to have more correct types:

* If the control is known to be present, `null` can be excluded.
* If the control is known to be absent, we can fail to just `null` instead of `AbstractControl<never>`, which is more correct
* For indeterminate cases (e.g. non-const arrays), we fail to `AbstractControl<any>|null`, which is exactly the same as before

This comes at the cost of a slightly messier `ÉµNavigate`, which is OK since it's an internal type anyway.

Here's an example of the improvement:

```
const fg = new FormGroup({
  foo: new FormControl('bar'),
});

// Before: an exclamation point is required
const val = fg.get('foo')!.value;

// After: the compiler knows the control exists and is non-null
const val = fg.get('foo').value;

// Before: `AbstractControl<never>`
const val = fg.get('oops');

// After: `null`
const val = fg.get('oops');
```

Inspired by [this YAQS question](https://yaqs.corp.google.com/eng/q/1033305634621095936), as well as feedback from @cexbrayat.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

compiler, core

### Description

In some scenarios it could be useful to import some modules dynamically without bundling by @angular/compiler

### Proposed solution

We could use function that would allow to import ES modules.

``` TS
import { importExternal, Injectable } from '@angular/core';

@Injectable()
export class ScriptsService {
  load() {
    return importExternal('./prebuild/my-lib.esm.js');
  }
}
```

### Alternatives considered

Currently we are able to achieve this in two ways:

1. By using `<script>`
``` TS
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';

@Injectable()
export class ScriptsService {
  load() {
    const script = document.body.appendChild(document.createElement('script'));
    script.type = 'module';
    script.src = './prebuild/my-lib.esm.js';
    return new Promise((resolve) => {
      script.onload = resolve;
    });
  }
}
```

2. By using `webpackIgnore`
``` TS
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';

@Injectable()
export class ScriptsService {
  load() {
    // @ts-ignore
    return import(/* webpackIgnore: true */ './prebuild/my-lib.esm.js');
  }
}
```

### Is this a regression?

- [X] Yes, this behavior used to work in the previous version

### The previous version in which this bug was not present was

13.2.4

### Description

I have created a loading wait service which uses MatSpinner based upon existing code example

https://medium.com/@velenra/using-angular-material-spinner-with-cdk-overlay-8ab92bfbafee
https://stackblitz.com/edit/mat-spinner-and-cdk-overlay-moxmh3

The issue I am experiencing since upgrading Angular beyond 13.2.4 is the background displays but the spinner is not longer displaying.  Nothing is displayed in the browser console that I can see.

The code for the spinner is

```javascript
import { Overlay, OverlayRef } from "@angular/cdk/overlay";
import { ComponentPortal } from "@angular/cdk/portal";
import { Injectable } from "@angular/core";
import { MatSpinner } from "@angular/material/progress-spinner";

// spinner so overlay and doesn't require separate component
// https://medium.com/@velenra/using-angular-material-spinner-with-cdk-overlay-8ab92bfbafee
// https://stackblitz.com/edit/mat-spinner-and-cdk-overlay-moxmh3

@Injectable({
  providedIn: "root"
})
export class LoadingWaitService {
  private readonly overlayRef: OverlayRef = null;
  private showCount = 0;

  constructor(private readonly overlay: Overlay) {
    this.overlayRef = this.overlay.create({
      hasBackdrop: true,
      backdropClass: "dark-backdrop",
      positionStrategy: this.overlay.position()
        .global()
        .centerHorizontally()
        .centerVertically()
    });
  }

  show() {
    this.showCount++;
    if (this.showCount === 1 && !this.overlayRef.hasAttached()) {
      const spinnerRef = this.overlayRef.attach(new ComponentPortal(MatSpinner));
      spinnerRef.instance.color = "accent";
    }
  }

  hide() {
    this.showCount--;
    if (this.showCount > 0)
      return;
    this.showCount = 0;
    setTimeout(() => {
      if (this.showCount === 0)
        this.overlayRef.detach();
    }, 500);
  }
}
```




### Reproduction

Steps to reproduce:
1.  Upgrade package.json from 13.2.4 to latest 13 version
2.  re run the application and no spinner


### Expected Behavior

The spinner displays after upgrading to new version of Angular

### Actual Behavior

The spinner no longer display after Angular upgrade

### Environment

- Angular:  cli/13.3.6, core/13.3.9
- CDK/Material: cdk/13.3.7, material/13.3.7
- Browser(s): Chrome
- Operating System (e.g. Windows, macOS, Ubuntu): Windows

### Feature Description

> Submitting as a Feature as I'm pretty sure the below scenario isn't officially supported by MDL.

[StackBlitz Scenario](https://stackblitz.com/edit/tab-embedded-menu)

When building out child routes accessed via a `<nav mat-tab-nav-bar>`, it's helpful to provide a button or menu exposing common functionality directly within the tab panel (vs. adding another panel parallel or adjacent to the tab panel). This technically works by linking a `mat-tab-link` to a menu, but it triggers the following console errors when the menu is opened / closed:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/14102723/169138122-38153fea-68a0-4339-9abf-728b2693c6e1.png)

If I change the menu trigger to a simple `<a mat-button>`, the styling for the button does not conform to the styling of the tabs in the nav panel:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/14102723/169138416-fdefea31-99b9-4e15-8b1d-edf271159643.png)

Recommendation would be to adjust styling for `mat-button` to to conform to tab styling when embedded in a `mat-tab-nav-bar`:

```scss
nav.mat-tab-nav-bar .mat-button {
  height: 48px;
  padding: 0 24px;
  opacity: .6;
  text-align: center;
  display: inline-flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  white-space: nowrap;
  vertical-align: top;
  text-decoration: none;
  position: relative;
  overflow: hidden;
}
```

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/14102723/169138952-2b87435b-d10a-4875-8e2d-e72767cb0421.png)


